The 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

-entry of a product is the product of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row of the left matrix with the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 column of the right matrix.
 Therefore the product will have as many rows as the left matrix and as
 many columns as the right matrix.
 In this example, that means 2 rows and 1 column.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1,1\text{-entry: } & \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-3 & 0 & 1\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
3\\
4
\end{array}\right]=1\\
2,1\text{-entry: } & \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & 5 & 7\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
3\\
4
\end{array}\right]=45
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Placing the right matrix just to the right and below the left matrix can
 help keep this straight:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-3 & 0 & 1\\
2 & 5 & 7
\end{array}\right] & \left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
45
\end{array}\right]\\
 & \left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
3\\
4
\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The answer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
45
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
