: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\mathbf{u}\Vert$
\end_inset

 is the length or norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, which is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathbf{u}^{T}\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Vert\mathbf{u}\Vert=\sqrt{\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & -6 & 12\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-6\\
12
\end{array}\right]}=\sqrt{2^{2}+(-6)^{2}+12^{2}}=\sqrt{4+36+144}=\sqrt{184}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:length-6"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is the distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, which is defined as the norm of their difference, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\mathbf{u-\mathbf{v}}\Vert$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Vert\mathbf{u-\mathbf{v}}\Vert=\left\Vert \left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-6\\
12
\end{array}\right]-\left[\begin{array}{c}
-6\\
-10\\
4
\end{array}\right]\right\Vert =\left\Vert \left[\begin{array}{c}
8\\
4\\
8
\end{array}\right]\right\Vert =\sqrt{8^{2}+4^{2}+8^{2}}=\sqrt{144}=12
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:length-10"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: The simplest way to check whether two vectors are orthogonal is to check
 whether their dot product is zero.
 In this case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{u}^{T}\mathbf{v}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & -6 & 12\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
-6\\
-10\\
-4
\end{array}\right]=2(-6)+(-6)(-10)+12(-4)=-12+60-48=0
\]

\end_inset

Since the dot product is zero, the vectors are orthogonal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:length-13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: In order for the vectors to be orthogonal their dot product must be zero.
 Setting the dot product equal to zero gives an equation that can be solved
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-2 & -6 & -3\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
-7\\
k\\
-10
\end{array}\right] & =0\\
(-2)(-7)+(-6)k+(-3)(-10) & =0\\
14-6k+30 & =0\\
44 & =6k\\
\frac{22}{3} & =k
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so the solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{22}{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

