: What makes any matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 upper triangular is that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k,\ell}=0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $k>\ell$
\end_inset

.
 That is, entries whose row number is greater than their column number are
 zero.
 After deleting the first row and some column of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, as shown below,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
\boxed{\star} & \boxed{\star} & \boxed{\star} & \boxed{\star} & \boxed{\cdots} & \boxed{\star}\\
0 & \star & \star & \boxed{\star} & \cdots & \star\\
0 & 0 & \star & \boxed{\star} & \cdots & \star\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \boxed{\star} & \cdots & \star\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \boxed{\vdots} & \ddots & \star\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \boxed{0} & \cdots & \star
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

there are two distinct regions of entries.
 Entries to the left of the deleted column have the same column index in
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\backslash i,j}$
\end_inset

 as they do in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Columns to the right of the deleted column have a column index one less
 than they do in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 All entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\backslash1,j}$
\end_inset

 have a row index one less than they do in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 In symbols [and 
\series bold
the start of the proof
\series default
],
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(U_{\backslash1,j})_{k,\ell} & =\begin{cases}
U_{k+1,\ell} & \text{if }\ell<j\\
U_{k+1,\ell+1} & \text{if }\ell\geq j
\end{cases}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $k>\ell$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1>\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1>\ell+1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{k+1,\ell}=U_{k+1,\ell+1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\backslash1,j})_{k,\ell}=0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $k>\ell$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

