 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 matrix, it is upper triangular and 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(\left[U_{1,1}\right]\right)=U_{1,1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
\shape italic
[This establishes part (i) of the proof.
 The claim is true for the particular value 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.]
\series default
\shape default
 Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}\cdots U_{k,k}$
\end_inset

 for some (arbitrary) value 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 greater than or equal to one and arbitrary upper triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
\shape italic
[That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an upper triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

, then the proposition is true.
 To complete the proof, we must use this information to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 upper triangular matrix then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}\cdots U_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

.]
\series default
\shape default
 Additionally, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 upper triangular matrix.
 By definition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det U=(-1)^{1+1}U_{1,1}\det U_{\backslash1,1}+(-1)^{1+2}U_{1,2}\det U_{\backslash1,2}\cdots+(-1)^{1+3}U_{1,3}\det U_{\backslash1,3}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\backslash1,j}$
\end_inset

 has a zero on its diagonal whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $j>1$
\end_inset

, all terms except the first are zero.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det U=(-1)^{1+1}U_{1,1}\det U_{\backslash1,1}.\label{eq:determinant-expansion-upper-triangular}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\backslash1,1}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix, its determinant is the product of the entries on its diagonal 
\series bold
\shape italic
[this is the inductive hypothesis]
\series default
\shape default
, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U_{\backslash1,1}=U_{2,2}U_{3,3}\cdots U_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this expresion into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant-expansion-upper-triangular"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}U_{3,3}\cdots U_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

, and the proof is complete.
